The '''Aquarius Stream''' is a [[Stellar_kinematics#Stellar_streams|stellar stream]] located in the [[Milky Way|Milky Way Galaxy]]. It is so named because most of the stars in the stream lie in the direction of the [[Aquarius (constellation)|Aquarius constellation]]. At its nearest point it is about 2000 light years from Earth; At its farthest it is about 30,000 light years away. It is the closest stellar stream to Earth yet found, and the youngest having formed about 700 million years ago. The stream was discovered in late 2010 by a team of astronomers involved in the RAdial Velocity Experiment (RAVE) survey led by [[New Zealand]]er Mary Williams.<ref>[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2011/02/110207-milky-way-galaxy-aquarius-stream-snack-space-science/ Galaxy "Crumbs" Found in Milky Way—Proof of Recent Feeding] National Geographic, Feb 7, 2011</ref><ref name="Stuff.co.nz_4661795">{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/4661795/Kiwi-astronomer-in-orbit-over-find |title=Kiwi astronomer 'in orbit' over find |author=Chug, Kiran |date=16 February 2011 |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref>
