{{Speciesbox | name = Chinese dormouse | status = DD | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite journal |author=Johnston, C. |author2=Smith, A.T. |last-author-amp=yes |title=''Chaetocauda sichuanensis'' |journal=[[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] |volume=2016 |page=e.T6860A22222574 |publisher=[[IUCN]] |year=2016 |url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/6860/0 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-1.RLTS.T6860A22222574.en |access-date=9 November 2017}}</ref> | display_parents = 2 | genus = Chaetocauda | parent_authority = Wang, 1985 | species = sichuanensis | authority = Wang, 1985 }}
The '''Chinese dormouse''' or '''Sichuan dormouse''' (''Chaetocauda sichuanensis'') is a species of [[dormouse]] found in subalpine mixed forests in northern [[Sichuan]], [[China]], where it is known from [[Jiuzhaigou]] and Wanglang Nature Reserves. It is known only from two captured female specimens taken in the [[Wanglang Natural Reserve]], and was first described by Wang Youzhi in 1985 and relisted by Corbet and Hill (1991, 1992) under a new [[genus]] as ''Chaetocauda sichuanensis''. It is currently the only member of the genus ''Chaetocauda''. The two specimens had head and body lengths of 90mm and 91mm and tail lengths of 92mm and 102mm, respectively. They weighed 24.5 and 36.0 g. It is nocturnal and arboreal, nesting in trees around 3 metres above the ground, and was found above an altitude of 2500m above sea level. It is classified as endangered by the [[IUCN]] as of the 2004 Red List due to its small, isolated habitat. [http://www.iucnredlist.org/search/details.php?species=6860]
==References== {{Reflist}} *Wang, Youzhi. 1985. A new genus and species of Gliridae. Acta Theriologica Sinica, Vol. 5 (1985), pp.&nbsp;67–75.
