'''H6N2''' is an [[avian influenza]] [[virus]] with two forms: one has a low and the other a high [[pathogen]]icity. Avian derived from the [[Latin]] word ''avis'' for "[[bird]]." It can cause a serious problem for [[poultry]], and also infects ducks as well.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jackwood|first1=MW|last2=Suarez|first2=DL|last3=Pantin-Jackwood|first3=MJ|last4=Spackman|first4=E|last5=Woolcock|first5=P|last6=Cardona|first6=C.|title=Biologic characterization of chicken-derived H6N2 low pathogenic avian influenza viruses in chickens and ducks|journal=Avian Dis.|date=2010|volume=54|issue=1|pages=120–125|pmid=20408410|doi=10.1637/8987-070909-resnote.1}}</ref> H6N2 subtype is considered to be a non-pathogenic chicken virus, the host still unknown, but could strain from feral animals, and/or aquatic bird reservoirs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Webby|first1=Richard J.|last2=Woolcock|first2=Peter R.|last3=Krauss|first3=Scott L.|last4=Webster|first4=Robert G.|title=Reassortment and Interspecies Transmission of North American H6N2 Influenza Viruses|journal=Virology|date=2002|volume=295|pages=44–53|url=http://ac.els-cdn.com/S0042682201913418/1-s2.0-S0042682201913418-main.pdf?_tid=9ac8914e-0c0a-11e6-89f0-00000aab0f6b&acdnat=1461715216_5c6d4bad7173976558cc90e4a712a4a2|doi=10.1006/viro.2001.1341|pmid=12033764}}</ref> H6N2 along with H6N6 are viruses that are found to replicate in mice without preadaptation, and some have acquired the ability to bind to human-like receptors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wang|first1=Guojun|last2=Deng|first2=Guohua|last3=Shi|first3=Jianzhong|last4=Luo|first4=Weiyu|last5=Zhang|first5=Guoquan|last6=Zhang|first6=Qianyi|last7=Liu|first7=Liling|last8=Jiang|first8=Yongping|last9=Li|first9=Chengjun|last10=Sriwilaijaroen|first10=Nongluk|last11=Hiramatsu|first11=Hiroaki|last12=Suzuki|first12=Yasuo|last13=Kawaoka|first13=Yoshihiro|last14=Chen|first14=Hualan|authorlink14=Chen Hualan |title=H6 Influenza Viruses Pose a Potential Threat to Human Health|journal=Journal of Virology|date=15 April 2014|volume=88|issue=8|pages=3953–3964|doi=10.1128/JVI.03292-13|doi-access=free|issn=0022-538X|pmid=24501418|pmc=3993743}}</ref> Genetic markers for H6N2 include 22-amino acid stalk deletion in [[neuraminidase]] (NA) protein gene, increased [[N-glycosylation]], and a D144 mutation of the [[Haemagglutinin]] (HA) protein gene.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abolnik|first1=C.|last2=Bisschop|first2=S.|last3=Gerdes|first3=T.|last4=Olivier|first4=A.|last5=Horner|first5=R.|title=Outbreaks of avian influenza H6N2 viruses in chickens arose by a reassortment of H6N8 and H9N2 ostrich viruses.|journal=Virus Genes|date=2007|volume=34|issue=1|pages=37–45|pmid=16927114|doi=10.1007/s11262-006-0007-6}}</ref> Transmission of avian influenza viruses from wild aquatic birds to domestic birds usually cause subclinical infections, and occasionally, respiratory disease and drops in egg production.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jackwood|first1=MW|last2=Suarez|first2=DL|last3=Pantin-Jackwood|first3=MJ|last4=Spackman|first4=E|last5=Woolcock|first5=P|last6=Cardona|first6=C.|title=Biologic characterization of chicken-derived H6N2 low pathogenic avian influenza viruses in chickens and ducks|journal=Avian Dis.|date=2010|volume=54|issue=1|pages=120–125|pmid=20408410|doi=10.1637/8987-070909-resnote.1}}</ref> Some histological features presented in chicken infected with H6N2 are fibrinous yolk peritonitis, salpingitis, oophoritis, nephritis, along with swollen kidneys as well.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kinde|first1=Hailu|last2=Read|first2=Deryck H.|last3=Daft|first3=Barbara M.|last4=Hammarlund|first4=Marion|last5=Moore|first5=Janet|last6=Uzal|first6=Francisco|last7=Mukai|first7=Janee|last8=Woolcock|first8=Peter|title=he Occurrence of Avian Influenza A Subtype H6N2 in Commercial Layer Flocks in Southern California (2000–02): Clinicopathologic Findings|journal=Avian Diseases|date=September 2003|volume=47|issue=3|pages=1214–1218|doi=10.1637/0005-2086-47.s3.1214}}</ref>

==Signs and symptoms==
*sneezing and lacrimation
*prostration
*anorexia and fever
*sometimes swelling of the infraorbital sinuses with nasal mucous <ref>{{cite web|last1=McFerran|first1=J. B.|last2=McNulty|first2=M. S.|title=Acute Virus Infections of Poultry: A Seminar in the CEC Agricultural Research Programme, held in Brussels, June 13–14, 1985|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RJDcBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|date=6 December 2012}}</ref>

