'''HR 2562b''' is a [[substellar companion]] of [[debris disk]] host star [[HR 2562]].<ref name=Konopacky>{{cite journal|last=Konopacky|first=Quinn M.|last2=Rameau|first2=Julien|last3=Duchêne|first3=Gaspard|last4=Filippazzo|first4=Joseph C.|last5=Godfrey|first5=Paige A. Giorla|last6=Marois|first6=Christian|last7=Nielsen|first7=Eric L.|last8=Pueyo|first8=Laurent|last9=Rafikov|first9=Roman R.|date=2016|title=Discovery of a Substellar Companion to the Nearby Debris Disk Host HR 2562|bibcode=2016ApJ...829L...4K|arxiv=1608.06660|journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters|language=en|volume=829|issue=1|pages=L4|doi=10.3847/2041-8205/829/1/L4|issn=2041-8205}}</ref> Initially categorised as [[brown dwarf]], its exact mass is unknown, and is thought to be 30 ± 15 [[Jupiter mass|Jupiter masses]],<ref name=Konopacky/> and its luminosity is about two one-thousandths of a percent of a [[solar luminosity]].<ref name=Konopacky/>{{refn|group=note|The luminosity of HR 2562 b is log(''L''/{{solar luminosity}}) {{=}} −4.62 ± 0.12.<ref name=Konopacky/>}}  If classified as a brown dwarf, its [[spectral type]] of L7±3.<ref name=Konopacky/> It was first observed in 2016 using the [[Gemini Planet Imager]]. 

According to [[NASA Exoplanet Archive]], with a mass of {{jupiter mass|30}}, it is listed as the [[List of most massive exoplanets|most massive planet]].

