{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Ingemar Henry Lundquist | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | nationality = [[Sweden|Swedish]] | citizenship = Swedish and [[Americans|American]] | birth_name = Ingemar Henry Lundquist | birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|10|19}} | birth_place = [[Stockholm, Sweden]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2007|2|25|1921|10|19}} | death_place = [[Carmel Valley Village, California]] | resting_place = [[Mountain View Cemetery (Oakland, California)]] | resting_place_coordinates = 37°50′07″N 122°14′13″W | education = Stockholm Institute of Technology | spouse = Linda | parents = | children = Richard, Cristian | module = {{infobox engineering career | discipline = [[Mechanical Engineering]] | institutions = | practice_name = | employer = Torex, Inc., Ultimax, Inc., Vidamed, Inc. | significant_projects = [[Balloon Angioplasty]], [[Somnoplasty]], [[Transurethral needle ablation of the prostate|T.U.N.A.]] | significant_design = | significant_advance = | significant_awards = }} | signature = | signature_alt = }} __NOTOC__ '''Ingemar Henry Lundquist''' (born in [[Stockholm]], Sweden, October 19, 1921, died in [[Carmel Valley Village, California|Carmel Valley Village]], California, February 25, 2007) was a prolific [[inventor]] and [[mechanical engineer]].<ref name="kucklick">{{cite book |last= Kucklick |first= Theodore |authorlink= |title= The Medical Device R&D Handbook, Second Edition [Hardcover] |url= |accessdate= |year= 2012 |publisher= CRC Press |location= |isbn= 978-1-4398-1189-4 |page= 399 }}</ref>
== Early life and education == Lundquist graduated from the [[KTH Royal Institute of Technology|Stockholm Institute of Technology]] in 1945 with a mechanical engineering degree.<ref name="kucklick" /><ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.memorialsolutions.com/sitemaker/sites/PaulMo1/obit.cgi?user=588_ILundquist69 |title =Biography, Ingemar Henry Lundquist |last = |first = |date = |work =memorialsolutions.com |publisher =Memorial Solutions |accessdate =July 8, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=Monterey>{{cite news |url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/montereyherald/obituary.aspx?n=ingemar-henry-lundquist&pid=86761247 |title=Ingemar Henry Lundquist |type=memorial |newspaper=Monterey Herald |date=March 10, 2007 }}</ref> He migrated to the United States in 1948 and became an American citizen in 1950.<ref name="kucklick" /><ref name=Monterey/>
==Career== He worked for various medical technology companies in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]], including Advanced Cardiovascular Systems and E.P. Technologies.
=== Patents === Lundquist had hundreds of inventions,<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.patentbuddy.com/Inventor/Lundquist-Ingemar-H/239821 |title =Ingemar H. Lundquist inventor |last = |first = |date = |work =patentbuddy.com |publisher =Patent Buddy |accessdate =July 8, 2013 }}</ref> typically working in his garage or basement.<ref name="kucklick" /> He held more than a hundred patents.<ref name=Monterey/> His inventions included over the wire [[balloon angioplasty]],<ref>{{cite web |url =http://patents.com/us-4332254.html |title =System for filling and inflating and deflating a vascular dilating cathether assembly |last = |first = |date = |work =patents.com |publisher =patents.com |accessdate =July 8, 2013 }}</ref> [[Transurethral needle ablation of the prostate|T.U.N.A.]],<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.patentbuddy.com/Patent/5807309 |title =US Patent No: 5,807,309 Transurethral needle ablation device and method for the treatment of the prostate |last = |first = |date = |work =patentbuddy.com |publisher =Patent Buddy |accessdate =July 8, 2013 }}</ref> and [[somnoplasty]].<ref>{{cite web |url =https://www.google.com/patents/US5409453 |title =Steerable medical probe with stylets US 5409453 A |last = |first = |date = |work =google.com |publisher =Google |accessdate =July 8, 2013 }}</ref> He also worked on cardiac [[stem-cell therapy]].<ref name=Monterey/>
